7:{"title":"Vertigo","director":"Alfred Hitchcock","year":1958,"rating":9.6,"mood":"violet","story":"A retired detective with a fear of heights becomes dangerously fixated on a mysterious woman he has been hired to follow — and on the version of her he has invented in his mind.","why":"The purest depiction of destructive romantic obsession ever filmed. It is a love story about someone who falls in love with an image, not a person — and what that costs.","after":"You'll recognise the times you loved what you imagined someone to be.","direction":"Hitchcock uses the camera like a scalpel, cutting into obsession with surgical precision.","cinematography":"Robert Burks creates a San Francisco of impossible, hallucinatory beauty — reality as a fever dream.","musicSound":"Bernard Herrmann's score is arguably the greatest piece of cinematic music ever written.","impact":"Watching it feels like being inside the obsession, not observing it from outside.","overall":"The film cinema returns to when it wants to understand itself. Inexhaustible."}
8:{"title":"In the Mood for Love","director":"Wong Kar-wai","year":2000,"rating":9.5,"mood":"rose","story":"Two neighbours in 1962 Hong Kong discover their spouses are having an affair, and in the slow, aching process of that discovery, fall into a love they will never act on.","why":"About desire held so tightly it never releases — the obsession with what could have been. The most romantic film ever made about not happening.","after":"You'll understand that some loves are defined entirely by their restraint.","direction":"Wong Kar-wai shoots time as a texture — slow motion that makes the ordinary sacred.","cinematography":"Doyle's saturated close-ups of fabric, hands, faces make longing into something visible.","musicSound":"Shigeru Umebayashi's waltz plays on repeat — because some feelings don't end, they just recur.","impact":"It does not depict obsession. It induces it. You leave the film slightly in love with it.","overall":"Possibly the most beautiful film ever made. No contest."}
9:{"title":"Blue Is the Warmest Colour","director":"Abdellatif Kechiche","year":2013,"rating":8.8,"mood":"dusk","story":"A French teenager falls all-consumingly in love with a blue-haired art student, and the film follows their relationship from electric beginning through devastating end.","why":"First love as total immersion — the way a person can become your entire world before you know enough to protect yourself from it.","after":"You'll remember when another person was the whole universe and be grateful for having been that young.","direction":"Kechiche's close-up-heavy style makes the emotional intimacy feel overwhelming and real.","cinematography":"The face as landscape — extreme close-ups that become the film's primary emotional register.","musicSound":"Naturalistic sound design. The absence of score makes the human moments land harder.","impact":"Three hours that feel like a life compressed. The ending breaks you precisely because the love was real.","overall":"Divisive, consuming, unforgettable. The kind of film that changes what you think film can do."}
a:{"title":"Possession","director":"Andrzej Żuławski","year":1981,"rating":8.9,"mood":"fire","story":"A spy returns home to find his wife wants a divorce, and as he tries to understand why, reality itself begins to dissolve into horror and obsession.","why":"Romantic jealousy taken to its absolute logical extreme — love that becomes indistinguishable from madness. Terrifying and completely honest.","after":"You'll see how thin the line really is between love and possession.","direction":"Żuławski directs in a state of controlled hysteria that mirrors the film's subject.","cinematography":"Bruno Nuytten's restless camera never finds rest — neither do the characters, neither do you.","musicSound":"Andrzej Korzyński's score is pure dread dressed as love.","impact":"One of the few films that makes you feel the inside of a mental breakdown from within.","overall":"Not for every viewer, but for the right one at the right moment, it is irreplaceable."}
b:{"title":"Secretary","director":"Steven Shainberg","year":2002,"rating":8.4,"mood":"rose","story":"A fragile young woman begins working as a secretary and enters a complex, transformative relationship with her controlling employer.","why":"About desire that doesn't fit the approved shape — the specific obsession of finally being seen in exactly the way you need to be seen.","after":"You'll stop being ashamed of what you actually want.","direction":"Shainberg treats unconventional desire with dignity and even joy — remarkably rare.","cinematography":"Lush, slightly surreal visual palette that treats the office as a private universe.","musicSound":"Angelo Badalamenti brings his signature sense of beautiful unease.","impact":"Oddly tender for a film about control — because it's really about two people recognising each other.","overall":"A film that takes its subject seriously when almost no one else would."}
c:{"title":"Lolita","director":"Stanley Kubrick","year":1962,"rating":8.7,"mood":"ash","story":"A middle-aged professor becomes obsessively fixated on his landlady's teenage daughter, and the darkly comic tragedy of that fixation unfolds across America.","why":"The clinical anatomy of an obsession that knows it is wrong and proceeds anyway — a masterclass in the self-delusion of desire.","after":"You'll recognise the interior monologue of any obsession that rationalised itself into being.","direction":"Kubrick treats horror with deadpan black comedy — which makes it more disturbing, not less.","cinematography":"Oswald Morris photographs American banality as a kind of beautiful trap.","musicSound":"Nelson Riddle's jazz score is ironic accompaniment to moral catastrophe.","impact":"Makes you deeply uncomfortable, which is entirely the point. Extraordinary craft in service of that discomfort.","overall":"A film about the stories we tell ourselves to permit what we know is wrong."}
d:{"title":"Eyes Wide Shut","director":"Stanley Kubrick","year":1999,"rating":8.9,"mood":"night","story":"A doctor's marriage is shaken by his wife's confession of a fantasy, sending him on a nocturnal odyssey through New York's hidden erotic world.","why":"Obsession with what your partner is thinking — the specific jealousy of realising you don't know the interior of someone you've lived beside for years.","after":"You'll look at the people you love and wonder what you don't know about them, with something like gratitude.","direction":"Kubrick's final film is hypnotic, dreamlike, paced like a fever that never quite breaks.","cinematography":"The most beautifully lit Christmas lights in cinema — holiday warmth used as irony.","musicSound":"Shostakovich and Ligeti create sustained unease under a surface of holiday cheer.","impact":"You come out of it changed, though you cannot say exactly how. The best Kubrick films work that way.","overall":"His final gift, unresolved and perfect. Still being understood twenty-five years later."}
e:{"title":"Foxcatcher","director":"Bennett Miller","year":2014,"rating":8.6,"mood":"ash","story":"A wealthy, eccentric heir draws two wrestling brothers into his orbit and a relationship of patronage and obsession with devastating consequences.","why":"Obsession with ownership — the need to possess another person's talent, success, loyalty. Dark portrait of desire as control.","after":"You'll understand how obsession can wear the costume of admiration.","direction":"Miller keeps everything cold, slow, and suffused with dread from the first frame.","cinematography":"Greig Fraser's desaturated palette makes the American countryside feel like a crime scene.","musicSound":"Rob Simonsen's score is sparse, unnerving, wrong in exactly the right ways.","impact":"Channing Tatum's performance is one of cinema's great sustained acts of physical sadness.","overall":"One of the decade's most formally accomplished films. Stays with you like a bad dream."}
f:{"title":"Nights of Cabiria","director":"Federico Fellini","year":1957,"rating":9.1,"mood":"gold","story":"A resilient, irrepressible Roman prostitute searches for love, encountering false promises and betrayal while somehow maintaining her extraordinary spirit.","why":"About the obsessive human need to believe someone loves you — the dangerous, beautiful vulnerability of hope.","after":"You'll be humbled by Cabiria's refusal to stop believing. And ashamed, slightly, that you nearly gave up.","direction":"Fellini treats Cabiria with absolute love — his camera never mocks what it adored.","cinematography":"Aldo Tonti photographs the Roman margins with documentary warmth.","musicSound":"Nino Rota's theme is joy carrying sadness inside it like a secret.","impact":"The ending is cinema's great act of grace — transcendence arriving through devastation.","overall":"Giulietta Masina gives one of cinema's immortal performances. Unmissable."}
10:{"title":"Brokeback Mountain","director":"Ang Lee","year":2005,"rating":9.3,"mood":"dusk","story":"Two cowboys spend a summer together on a Wyoming mountain and fall into a love neither can fully accept — carrying it across decades and separate lives.","why":"About love that cannot be lived in the open — obsession with the unlived life. The particular destruction of a love you had to put away.","after":"You'll grieve every love you were not free to live.","direction":"Lee handles the sublime and the suppressed with equal and precise tenderness.","cinematography":"Rodrigo Prieto's landscape photography makes Wyoming a third character — witness to the impossible.","musicSound":"Gustavo Santaolalla's spare guitar score is the sound of longing itself.","impact":"The shirt scene is one of cinema's great moments — grief held in a physical object.","overall":"A modern American tragedy of the absolute first order."}
12:["world","obsession","d"]
13:["emotion","destructive-love","d"]
0:["-l06LWa9y3QJYd9Q3nt3y",[[["",{"children":[["world","obsession","d"],{"children":[["emotion","destructive-love","d"],{"children":["__PAGE__?{\"world\":\"obsession\",\"emotion\":\"destructive-love\"}",{}]}]}]},"$undefined","$undefined",true],["",{"children":[["world","obsession","d"],{"children":[["emotion","destructive-love","d"],{"children":["__PAGE__",{},[["$L1",[["$","div",null,{"aria-hidden":true,"className":"fixed inset-0 pointer-events-none z-0","style":{"background":"\n      radial-gradient(ellipse 60% 45% at 25% 20%, rgba(196,75,75,0.22) 0%, transparent 55%),\n      radial-gradient(ellipse 50% 40% at 80% 80%, rgba(140,30,30,0.16) 0%, transparent 60%)\n    "}}],["$","div",null,{"className":"relative overflow-hidden","children":[["$","$L2",null,{"worldSlug":"obsession"}],["$","$L3",null,{"currentPath":"/obsession/destructive-love"}],["$","div",null,{"className":"relative z-10 max-w-[1440px] mx-auto px-5 md:px-12","children":[["$","div",null,{"className":"flex items-center gap-3 text-[11px] tracking-[0.2em] uppercase text-ink-muted pt-10 pb-5 font-semibold","children":[["$","$L4",null,{"href":"/","className":"hover:text-ink transition-colors duration-300 no-underline flex items-center gap-2","children":"← All worlds"}],["$","span",null,{"className":"text-ink-faint","children":"/"}],["$","span",null,{"className":"text-ink","children":["World ","13"]}]]}],["$","section",null,{"className":"pb-20 md:pb-28","children":[["$","div",null,{"className":"mb-8 flex items-center gap-3 text-[11px] font-semibold uppercase tracking-[0.42em] text-accent","children":[["$","span",null,{"className":"inline-block h-px w-8 bg-accent"}],"World ","13"," · ",2," ","states"]}],["$","h1",null,{"className":"text-[64px] sm:text-[100px] md:text-[140px] lg:text-[180px] font-bold leading-[0.92] tracking-[-0.035em] text-ink mb-6","children":"Obsession"}],["$","p",null,{"className":"text-[18px] md:text-[24px] lg:text-[28px] leading-[1.4] text-ink-soft max-w-[760px] font-normal tracking-[-0.005em]","children":"Films for the dark passenger — the love, the work, the idea that colonised you. The films here understand that obsession is just desire with nowhere to go."}]]}]]}]]}],["$","main",null,{"className":"max-w-[1440px] mx-auto px-5 md:px-12 relative z-[1]","children":[["$","section",null,{"className":"border-b border-line","children":[["$","div",null,{"className":"flex items-center gap-3 text-[11px] tracking-[0.32em] uppercase text-ink-muted font-semibold pt-10 pb-4","children":[["$","span",null,{"className":"inline-block w-5 h-px bg-ink-faint"}],"Choose an emotion"]}],["$","div",null,{"className":"flex flex-wrap gap-2 md:gap-3 pb-8","children":[["$","$L4","destructive-love",{"href":"/obsession/destructive-love","className":"text-[14px] md:text-[15px] font-semibold tracking-[-0.005em] px-5 py-2.5 rounded-full transition-all duration-300 no-underline bg-accent text-bg shadow-[0_0_24px_rgba(19,237,255,0.35)]","children":"Destructive Love"}],["$","$L4","creative-obsession",{"href":"/obsession/creative-obsession","className":"text-[14px] md:text-[15px] font-semibold tracking-[-0.005em] px-5 py-2.5 rounded-full transition-all duration-300 no-underline bg-white/[0.06] text-ink-soft hover:text-ink hover:bg-white/[0.10] border border-white/[0.08]","children":"Creative Obsession"}]]}]]}],["$","section",null,{"className":"border-b border-white/8 py-12 md:py-16","children":["$","div",null,{"className":"max-w-[720px]","children":[["$","div",null,{"className":"mb-5 flex items-center gap-3","children":[["$","span",null,{"className":"h-px w-6 bg-accent/60"}],["$","span",null,{"className":"text-[10px] font-semibold uppercase tracking-[0.3em] text-accent/70","children":["On ","Destructive Love"]}]]}],["$","p",null,{"className":"text-[16px] font-normal leading-[1.8] text-ink-soft md:text-[18px]","children":"There is a kind of love that you know, from the first moment, is going to cost you. You see the damage it will do — to you, to them, to the ordinary life you were building — and you walk toward it anyway. You cannot explain this to anyone who has not felt it. You cannot explain it to yourself. These films do not judge that. They sit inside the heat of the decision and let it breathe. They do not pretend love is always wise. They understand that some of the most real things you will ever feel are exactly the ones that had no future."}]]}]}],["$","section",null,{"className":"py-16 md:py-20","children":[["$","div",null,{"className":"flex flex-col md:flex-row md:items-end md:justify-between gap-6 mb-10 md:mb-14","children":[["$","div",null,{"children":[["$","div",null,{"className":"flex items-center gap-3 mb-4 text-[11px] tracking-[0.32em] uppercase text-ink-muted font-semibold","children":[["$","span",null,{"className":"inline-block w-5 h-px bg-ink-faint"}],"Destructive Love"]}],["$","h2",null,{"className":"text-[32px] md:text-[44px] lg:text-[56px] font-bold leading-[1.05] tracking-[-0.025em] text-ink max-w-[820px]","children":"Films for the love that knew it was wrong and kept going."}]]}],["$","div",null,{"className":"text-[12px] tracking-[0.18em] uppercase text-ink-muted font-semibold md:text-right shrink-0","children":[["$","span",null,{"className":"block text-[44px] md:text-[56px] text-ink font-bold tracking-[-0.03em] normal-case leading-none","children":"10"}],["$","span",null,{"className":"mt-2 block","children":"Curated films"}]]}]]}],["$","div",null,{"className":"py-10 border-b border-white/6 mb-10","children":["$","$L5",null,{"films":[{"title":"Vertigo","director":"Alfred Hitchcock","year":1958,"rating":9.6,"mood":"violet","story":"A retired detective with a fear of heights becomes dangerously fixated on a mysterious woman he has been hired to follow — and on the version of her he has invented in his mind.","why":"The purest depiction of destructive romantic obsession ever filmed. It is a love story about someone who falls in love with an image, not a person — and what that costs.","after":"You'll recognise the times you